DEEP PACKET ANALYSIS
  CLIENT                              SERVER

State: CLOSED                       State: LISTEN
                                    (Server listening on port 80)

═══════════ STEP 1: SYN ════════════════════════════

TCP Packet from Client:
├── Flags: SYN (only)
├── Sequence Number: x (e.g., 1000) ← Random, arbitrary
├── Acknowledgment: 0 (not set in SYN)
├── Window Size: 64KB (buffer space client can receive)
├── MSS (Max Segment Size): 1460 bytes
└── Options: Timestamps, SACK, Window Scaling

Client State: SYN_SENT
Client stores: seq_client = 1000

                        Server receives
                        ↓
═══════════ STEP 2: SYN-ACK ════════════════════════

TCP Packet from Server:
├── Flags: SYN, ACK
├── Sequence Number: y (e.g., 2000) ← Server's random seq
├── Acknowledgment: x+1 (1001) ← "I received up to byte 1000"
├── Window Size: 65535 (larger buffer)
├── MSS: 1460
└── Options: (same as client)

Server State: SYN_RECEIVED
Server stores: seq_server = 2000, ack_client = 1001

Client receives
                        ↓
═══════════ STEP 3: ACK ════════════════════════════

TCP Packet from Client:
├── Flags: ACK (no SYN)
├── Sequence Number: x+1 (1001) ← Continue from before
├── Acknowledgment: y+1 (2001) ← "I received up to byte 2000"
├── Window Size: 64KB
└── (Can include data! First data packet)

Client State: ESTABLISHED
                        ↓
                Server State: ESTABLISHED

═══════════ CONNECTED & READY ══════════════════════

NOW DATA FLOWS:
Client sends: SEQ=1001, ACK=2001, DATA="GET / HTTP/1.1\r\n..."
Server sends: SEQ=2001, ACK=1XXX, DATA="HTTP/1.1 200 OK\r\n..."

TCP 3-Way Handshake (Deeper Dive)
Why Handshake Exists
Both sides need to:

Synchronize sequence numbers (for reliable ordering)
Advertise receive window (flow control)
Confirm connection parameters (MSS, options)
Establish state (both sides know connection exists)

TIME_WAIT()
Connection closes → Port 5000 released immediately
New connection tries to use port 5000
Old delayed packet arrives → confuses new connection
Result: Data corruption, connection errors

With TIME_WAIT (2×MSL = ~60 seconds):
Ensures all old packets are gone before port reuse
Port 5000 unusable for 60 seconds after close
Old packets safely expire
Safe to reopen port










ARP WORKFLOW()
Device A (192.168.1.100 / AA:AA:AA:AA:AA:AA)
  ↓
"WHO HAS 192.168.1.101? TELL 192.168.1.100"
  ↓ (ARP Request - BROADCAST to everyone on LAN)
  ↓
Device B (192.168.1.101 / BB:BB:BB:BB:BB:BB) receives
  ↓
Device B responds: "I'm 192.168.1.101, my MAC is BB:BB:BB:BB:BB:BB"
  ↓ (ARP Reply - UNICAST back to Device A)
  ↓
Device A caches: 192.168.1.101 → BB:BB:BB:BB:BB:BB
  ↓
Device A sends frame with:
  Source MAC: AA:AA:AA:AA:AA:AA
  Dest MAC: BB:BB:BB:BB:BB:BB
  Source IP: 192.168.1.100
  Dest IP: 192.168.1.101

  
